label: member of { tangible thing, line }
LinearObject-Tangible
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: member of { partially tangible thing , line }
items.comment:
The "collection-intersection" of LinearObject and PartiallyTangible (qq.v.). LinearObject_Tangible is the collection of all and only tangible, linearly-shaped objects. They might be straight or curved, bounded or unbounded, finite or (at least in principle) infinite. All tangible linear objects are in fact three-dimensional.

In certain contexts, a long and thin tangible object or region might be treated as a line. For example, a wire might serve as a line in a communication network; a river might demarcate the boundary between two countries; a line drawn in the sand might serve as a volleyball court boundary.

Important specializations of LinearObject_Tangible are CordlikeObject and EdgeOnObject.

items.comment: A linkup is a meeting of friendly ground forces and occurs in a variety of circumstances. It happens when an advancing force reaches an objective area previously seized by an airborne or air assault when an encircled element breaks out to rejoin friendly forces or a force comes to the relief of an encircled force maneuver forces meet. Both forces may be moving toward each other or one may be stationary. Whenever possible, joining forces exchange as much information as possible prior to the start of an operation.

predicate specifying inter-argument types
InterArgTypePredicate
items.comment:
The subcollection of both InterArgConstraintPredicate and ArgTypePredicate (qq.v.) whose instances are used to put conditional argument-type constraints on polyadic relations in regards to two of their argument-places. Each instance of InterArgTypePredicate specifies, with respect to a given Relation, that one of its arguments (the "dependent" one) must be of a certain type, contingent upon another of its argument's (the "independent" one's) either being of a certain (possibly different) type or being identical to a certain thing. Depending on the particular inter-arg-type predicate, an argument's "type" might be specified in terms of either isa or genls. (For more details see the nearest specializations of ArgTypePredicate and InterArgTypePredicate.)

An inter-argument-type predicate PRED has argument-places for designating the relation and the two argument-types (or an argument-type and a particular thing); the (numerically-specified) identities of the relation's corresponding dependent and independent arguments is in most cases fixed (as in interArgIsa1_2), but is in some cases variable and specified via two additional argument-places of PRED's (as in interArgIsa). In cases of the former sort, where the relation's argument-places are fixed, PRED is a TernaryPredicate that takes as it first argument (or "arg1") a relation, as its arg2 the type specified for the relation's independent argument, and as its arg3 the type (or thing) specified (contingently) for the dependent argument.

See also the specializations InterArgIsaPredicate and InterArgEqualsIsaPredicate.

intentional mental event
IntentionalMentalEvent
items.comment: A specialization of both AtLeastPartiallyMentalEvent and IntentionalMentalSituation (qq.v.). This is the collection of (at least partially) mental events whose instances are characterized by intentionality: they are "of" or "about" some thing external to themselves. Thoughts and acts of perception are two common types of intentional mental events. Thus, a particular act of thinking about the Eiffel Tower and a particular act of seeing the Eiffel Tower are both intentional mental events, each having (at least) the Eiffel Tower as their object. Any thing whatsoever can in principle be the object of an intentional mental event: I can think about a certain physical object, an Event, a Relation, an attribute, a Proposition, a mental state (my own or another's), a set, a Collection, or anything else. Mental events that are _not_ intentional, and thus not in this collection, include non-localized pain experiences, and at least some instances of ExperiencingEmotion (q.v.). Note that, although they are indirectly related (see e.g. PurposefulMentalActivity), the sense of "intentional" described above is not to be confused with its other sense as an antonym of "accidental". Nor is it to be confused with the logico-semantic concept of _intensional_ meaning. See also IntentionalMentalState, objectOfMentalSituation, and thinksAbout.

Note that some units of measure, e.g. SecondsDuration, Barrel_UnitOfVolume, Watt, and Byte, are instances of both InternationalUnitOfMeasure and USUnitOfMeasure. (See UniversalUnitOfMeasure.) Two important specializations of InternationalUnitOfMeasure are MetricUnitOfMeasure and SIUnitOfMeasure (qq.v.).

Note, too, that LectureSeries_CW is not a spec of TextualPCW, as the performances of their instances (FormalLectureSeries_IBTs) often involve much more than a simple expression of propositions, e.g., simple experiments.

items.comment:
A second-order collection that facets and partitions (see facets_Partition) the collection LinearObject (q.v.), according to how many spatial dimensions a linear-object has. Geometric lines and line-segments are of course one-dimensional. In a two-dimensional contexts, however, certain "ribbon"-shaped regions (e.g. rivers depicted on a map) might be treated as lines. And in three-dimensional contexts (e.g. the physical world), certain long thin 3-D tangible objects (e.g. wires or pencil markings) are often treated as lines. The instances of LinearObjectTypeByDimensions are thus: LinearObject_OneDimensional, LinearObject_TwoDimensional, and LinearObject_ThreeDimensional.

Note that some poly-dimensional objects will be borderline and/or context-dependent cases with respect to whether they are LinearObjects, as opposed to being Surfaces or solids.

A collection of mental states whose instances are characterized by intentionality: they are "of" or "about" some thing external to themselves. Propositional attitudes (as held by particular agents) are a common type of intentional mental state. Thus, believing that the Eiffel Tower is located in Paris is an intentional mental state that has the Eiffel Tower and the city of Paris (and arguably the located-in relation as well) as its objects. Any thing whatsoever can in principle be the object of an intentional mental state: I can have a belief (or doubt, wish, etc.) about a certain physical object, an event, a relation, an attribute, a proposition, a mental state (my own or another's), a set, a collection, or anything else. (Note that the above mentioned belief about the Eiffel Tower and Paris is arguably not itself about the _proposition_ that the Eiffel Tower is in Paris. But now note that my belief in the content of the sentence preceding this one clearly _is_, in part, about that proposition.) Mental states that are _not_ intentional, and thus not in this collection, include moods, such as being in a general state of happiness or depression. (These states are to be distinguished from an experience of feeling happy or depressed, which are mental _events_ rather than states. One can be in an uninterrupted state of depression for weeks, even though one doesn't feel depressed continuously throughout that time; e.g. one would not feel depressed while asleep.) Note that, although they are indirectly related, the sense of "intentional" described above is not to be confused with its other sense as an antonym of "accidental". See also IntentionalMentalEvent and objectOfMentalSituation.

IntentionalMentalState

label: energy that some tangible thing has the physical attribute
KineticEnergyQuantity
items.comment:
A specialization of EnergyQuantity. Each instance of KineticEnergyQuantity is a quantity of translational (as opposed to rotational) kinetic energy had by some object This collection is simply a rewrite of: 
(SubcollectionOfWithRelationFromTypeFn EnergyQuantity kineticEnergyOfObject PartiallyTangible).
In classical mechanics, the kinetic energy of an object is defined as (1/2)mv^2, i.e., 0.5 times the mass of the object times the square of the speed (i.e. magnitude of velocity) of the object. One way of expressing this in CycL is: 
(mathEquals
  (MeasurementAtFn
    ((QPQuantityFn KineticEnergyQuantity) ?OBJ) ?TEMP-THING)
  (TimesFn
    0.5
    (MeasurementAtFn
      ((QPQuantityFn Mass) ?OBJ) ?TEMP-THING)
    (SquaredFn
      (MeasurementAtFn
        ((QPQuantityFn Speed) ?OBJ) ?TEMP-THING)))).

The collection of BinaryPredicates that are irreflexive. A binary predicate PRED is an instance of IrreflexiveBinaryPredicate only if, for every THING that satisfies the single-argument type-constraints (i.e. argIsa and argGenls; see admittedArgument) on both of PRED's argument-places, (not (PRED THING THING)) holds.

To rule out "vacuous" cases, there is an additional necessary condition for irreflexivity: the constraints on PRED's two argument-places must be co-satisfiable (see cosatisfiableInArgs). Without this requirement, any binary predicate whose arguments were constrained in mutually-disjoint ways would trivially (and counterintuitively) count as irreflexive. See #$NoteOnArgumentCosatisfiabilityRequirement

Examples of irreflexive binary predicates include spouse, causes_ThingProp, northOf, and temporallyDisjoint.

A collection of service-providing organizations. Each InternetServiceProvider, or ISP, provides its clients with access to the Internet. Access may be provided via a telephone number for the client's modem to connect to a modem at the ISP, a dedicated high-speed line, cable modem, cellular or sattelite connection, or more modern technologies. Note that the criterion for being "straight" in the present sense varies from context to context. For example, the standard of straightness for limning a football field is less precise than that for pure geometry.

Important geometrical specializations of LinearObject_Straight are Line_Straight, Ray_Geometrical, and LineSegment.

label: irreversible reformulation

items.comment: A property of reformulator rules. (2) If RULE, when applied in the backward direction to a given expression PRE-FORM, yields the expression POST-FORM, then RULE, when applied in the forward direction to POST-FORM, does not yield PRE-FORM. (3) Applying RULE in the forward direction is impossible. (4) Applying RULE in the backward direction is impossible. See also OneWayReformulation_Forward and OneWayReformulation_Backward

label: inter-arg isa predicate
InterArgIsaPredicate
items.comment: The subcollection of both InterArgTypePredicate and ArgIsaPredicate (qq.v.) whose instances are used to put conditional isa based argument-type constraints on polyadic relations in regards to two of their argument-places. Each instance of InterArgIsaPredicate specifies, with respect to a given Relation, that one of its arguments (the "dependent" one) must be an instance of (isa) a certain collection, contingent upon another of its argument's (the "independent" one's) being an instance of a certain (possibly different) collection. An inter-argument-isa predicate PRED has argument-places for designating the relation and the two collections serving as argument-types; the (numerically-specified) identities of the relation's corresponding dependent and independent arguments is in most cases fixed (as in interArgIsa1_2), but is in some cases variable and specified via two additional argument-places of PRED's (as in interArgIsa). In cases of the former sort, where the relation's argument-places are fixed, PRED is a TernaryPredicate that takes as it first argument (or "arg1") a relation, as its arg2 the type specified for the relation's independent argument, and as its arg3 the type specified (contingently) for the dependent argument.

lattice order
Lattice-LatticeTheoretic
items.comment: The collection of all mathmetical structures called 'lattices' in Lattice Theory (this is not the same concept as the crystalline or grid lattices studied in Crystallography and Group Theory). A Lattice_LatticeTheoretic is often defined in different but equivalent ways. To define a lattice using ordering relation, it is a PartialOrdering ORDER in which each pair of elements of the baseSet S of ORDER has an R-smallest upper bound and an R-greatest lower bound, where R is the ordering relation on S. To define a lattice using operations, it is a mathematical structure with two operations MEET and JOIN on the baseSet S of the structure that satisfy the commutative laws, the associative laws, the idempotent laws and the absorption laws. Note that the correspondence of these two different ways of defining lattices is characterized by the following: for all X, Y in S, Y = (JOIN X Y) <=> R(X Y) <=> X = (MEET X Y). See meetFunctionOnLattice and joinFunctionOnLattice.

label: internal tension
InternalTension
items.comment:
A VectorIntervalType and specialization of ForceVector. Each instance of InternalTension is a ForceVector that represents the equal and opposite forces that two halves of a stretched object are exerting on each other. (Note: using halves instead of arbitrary segments is just a matter of convention.)

To illustrate, consider a tire hanging by a rope from a tree branch. To say that the rope has an InternalTension of 10 newtons upward (or equivalently, downward) is to say that the top half of the rope is exerting 10 N of upward force on the bottom half, and the bottom half is exerting 10 N of downward force on the top half.

To represent the forces that the stretched rope exerts on the branch and the tire, use ExertedTension

linear object type by straightness
LinearObjectTypeByStraightness
items.comment:
A SecondOrderCollection that facets and covers (see facets_Covering) the collection LinearObject, according to how close a linear object is to being completely straight. Relative straightness, in the sense relevent here, is measured roughly in terms of the dimensionality of a space in which a linear object can be embedded. For example, a perfectly straight line segment (see LineSegment_Straight) can be embedded in a one-dimensional space; some curved line segments (e.g. Arcs) require at least a two-dimensional space for embedding; and other curved line segments (e.g. linear spirals) require three dimensions for embedding. The reified instances of LinearObjectTypeByStraightness include the successively-subsuming collections LinearObject_Straight, LinearObject_Planar, and LinearObject itself.

Note that the qualifier "roughly" is used above because some LinearObjects are actually poly-dimensional (e.g. a piece of wire is 3-D), and we also want to distinguish between "straight" and "planar" and "non-planar" poly-dimensional linear objects (e.g. pins vs. staples vs. springs). So some poly-dimensional linear objects will be borderline and/or context-dependent cases with respect to which straightness category they belong to.

A specialization of LinearObject (q.v.). LinearObject_Finite is the collection of all and only linearly-shaped objects that are finite in length. They might be straight or curved, tangible or intangible. A finite linear object might have two end points (e.g. a straight line segment), no end points (e.g. a closed curve or simple loop), or one end point (e.g. a loop with a "tail").

An important specialization of LinearObject_Finite is LineSegment, whose instances are strictly one-dimensional.

Cf. LinearObject_Infinite.

Low explosives undergo autocombustion at rates that vary from a few centimeters per second to approximately 400 meters per second. Low explosives are normally employed as propellants and they also include smokeless powders and pyrotechnics such as flares and illumination devices. See also HighExplosive. Note that high explosives detonate (see Detonation), whereas low explosives deflagrate (see Deflagration).

list of vertices
ListOfVertices
items.comment:
A specialization of List. Each instance of ListOfVertices is a list of Points whose length is at least three, and which contains no three consecutive (including rotationally-consecutive) members that are collinearPoints. (Note that there are two "rotationally-consecutive" triples in such a list: (i) the sublist consisting of the second-to-last, last, and first members of the list and (ii) the sublist consisting of the last, first, and second members of the list.)

Each ListOfVertices POINTLIST of length N is a list of the vertices of some (actually, many) two-dimensional geometrical figure(s) whose boundary is the closed LineString that "connects-the-dots" between the consecutive points in POINTLIST. If all the points in POINTLIST happen to lie in the same Plane (see coplanarPoints) and the closed line-string they define is geometrically simple (see LocallyEuclideanSpatialThing), then POINTLIST is a list of the vertices of a unique N-sided Polygon.

label: inter arg constraint predicate
InterArgConstraintPredicate
items.comment: The collection of ArgConstraintPredicates used to put conditional constraints on polyadic relations in regard to two of their argument-places (or, in a few cases, to put a conditional constraint on relations in regard to two different features of one argument-place). Each instance of InterArgConstraintPredicate specifies, with respect to a given Relation, that one of its argument-places (the "dependent" one) has a certain feature, contingent upon one (usually a different one) of its argument-place's (the "independent" one's) having a certain (possibly different) feature. The "features" in question might be either argument-type specifications (see InterArgTypePredicate) or format specifications (see InterArgFormatPredicate). An inter-argument constraint predicate PRED has argument-places for designating the relation and the two features; the identities of the relation's corresponding dependent and independent argument-places might be fixed (as in interArgIsa1_2) or might be variable and specified (by number) via two additional argument-places of PRED's (as in interArgIsa).

label: Joint Operations graphic
JointOperationsGraphic
items.comment: JointOperationsGraphic (JOG) maps are TopographicMaps which are based on standard 1:250,000 medium-scale military topographic maps, but they contain additional information needed to conduct joint air-ground operations. JOG maps are produced both in ground (JOG-G) and air (JOG-A) formats. See JointOperationsGraphic_Ground and JointOperationsGraphic_Air. The topographic information is identical on both, but the ground version shows elevations and contour in meters and the air version shows them in feet. Layer (elevation) tinting and relief shading are added as an aid to interpolating relief. Both versions emphasize air landing facilities (shown in purple), but the air version has additional symbols to identify aids and obstructions to air navigation. Each JOG map is identified by an ID string which is determined by the geographic location which the map covers. See JOGMapFn and idStringForJOGMap

label: type of interconvertible unit
InterconvertibleUnitType
items.comment:
A collection of collections and a specialization of FunctionType. Each instance IUT of InterconvertibleUnitType is a collection of UnitOfMeasure (q.v.) functions that are interconvertible. That is, each instance of IUT is a function used to measure quantities in units that are convertible into units measured by any of the other functions in IUT (see interconvertibleUnits).

Examples of InterconvertibleUnitTypes include UnitOfTime, UnitOfDistance and UnitOfComputerStorageCapacity. Thus, UnitOfTime includes the functions HoursDuration and MinutesDuration, and any duration denoted by applying one of these functions can also be expressed in terms of the other; e.g. (HoursDuration 1) equals (MinutesDuration 60).

Note that not all ontologically interesting specializations of UnitOfMeasure constitute interconvertible types. For example, UnitOfRate has both TimesPerDay and MilesPerHour as instances; but the quantities returned by either one of these functions are not convertible into quantities returned by the other.

inter arg not isa predicate
InterArgNotIsaPredicate
items.comment: The subcollection of both InterArgTypePredicate and ArgNotIsaPredicate (qq.v.) whose instances are used to put conditional isa based argument-type constraints on polyadic relations in regards to two of their argument-places. Each instance of InterArgNotIsaPredicate specifies, with respect to a given Relation, that one of its arguments (the "dependent" one) must _not_ be an instance of (isa) a certain collection, contingent upon another of its argument's (the "independent" one's) being an instance of a certain (possibly different) collection. An inter-argument-isa predicate PRED has argument-places for designating the relation and the two collections serving as argument-types; the (numerically-specified) identities of the relation's corresponding dependent and independent arguments is in most cases fixed (as in interArgNotIsa1_2), but is in some cases variable and specified via two additional argument-places of PRED's (as in interArgNotIsa). In cases of the former sort, where the relation's argument-places are fixed, PRED is a TernaryPredicate that takes as it first argument (or "arg1") a relation, as its arg2 the type specified for the relation's independent argument, and as its arg3 the type forbidden (contingently) for the dependent argument.

A specialization of Tuple. Each instance of List is a finite sequence of things with a first and last member-position, with each member-position other than the last having a successor member-position. As with tuples generally, lists allow for repetition of their members, so that the same item can appear at multiple member-positions in the same list. A list can be represented formally as a function from a finite index set of counting numbers, beginning with one, into the domain of all Things (but note that Lists are _not_ explicitly represented as functions in the Cyc ontology). Unlike an instance of Series (q.v.), a list is purely abstract (i.e. both aspatial and atemporal), and the only implied relation between an item and its successor in a list is the successor relation of the list itself. Technically, List is more specific than Tuple only in that the index set (see tupleIndexSet) for a given list must be the counting numbers in their usual order (or some initial segment thereof), whereas the index set for a tuple, generally speaking, might be any set whatsoever.

List

A specialization of RationalNumber. Each instance of Integer is a whole number with no fractional remainder. An integer may be positive (e.g. 42), zero, or negative (e.g. -42).

Note that, in the KB browser, a fixed- or floating-point number representation such as `42.00' should not be assumed to refer to the integer 42. For it might only appear to correspond to that integer within the tolerance of its representation, and might in fact be an approximation to a non-integer number such as 42.0003.

Also note that, unlike Integer, SubLInteger (q.v.) is a collection of integer-denoting expressions in the SubL programming language rather than a collection of integers themselves. Still, (genls SubLInteger Integer) holds, but only under a special interpretation of genls forced by the fact that SubLInteger is a #$quotedCollection (q.v).)

label: manifold
LocallyEuclideanSpatialThing
items.comment:
A specialization of SpatialThing. Roughly speaking, a spatial thing is a LocallyEuclideanSpatialThing if it has no self-intersections. For example, a line-segment is geometrically simple if it can be traced without visiting the same point twice; a two-dimensional region is geometrically simple if its boundary is simple.

More formally, an N-dimensional spatial thing THING is geometrically simple if and only if, for every point in the interior of THING, there exists a neighborhood of the point contained in the interior of THING and a homeomorphism (open and continuous bijection) that maps the neighborhood onto an open subset of N dimensional Euclidean space.

While CycL currently lacks the vocabulary to codify the formal definition, we can state restricted forms of it for certain classes of spatial things, and do so in the cases that are of immediate interest. For these, see the reified specializations of this collection.

items.comment: A specialization of VetoingSomething. Each instance of LineItemVeto is an event in which a line of a bill, as opposed to an entire bill, is vetoed.

IroquoianLanguageFamily
items.comment: Amerindian languages of the eastern Great Lakes and southern Appalachian area

label: assertion justification strength
JustificationStrength
items.comment: Instances of JustificationStrength are attribute values which indicate the argumentational strength of a justification for an assertion in a context. The two most important examples are Monotonic_JustificationStrength and Default_JustificationStrength. See also assertionStrength.

label: left riverbank
LeftRiverbank
items.comment: The collection of left bank of a river. See <font color="#ff0000">#$LeftBankFn</font>.

label: lending library organization
LendingLibrary-Organization
items.comment: The collection of all instances of Library_Organization that lend materials to their users and permit them to remove those materials from the premises of the LendingLibrary_Organization.

label: recruiting
JobRecruitmentServiceEvent
items.comment: The collection of service events in which the providerOfService finds new people to work in a company, join an organization, do a job etc.

killing that is a subevent of asphyxiation

items.subClassOf: event that inherently involves a change of state
items.comment: A collection of events; a subcollection of IntrinsicStateChangeEvent. In each InterchangeTwoThings, someone causes something to change places with something else.

InterchangeTwoThings
air locomotion
Locomotion-Air
items.comment: The collection of all instances of LocomotionProcess in which the locomotor is in_ImmersedFully and supported by some GaseousTangibleThing. Includes both the movement of an airplane in flight, and the movement of birds and bats while flying.

label: dried up lake
LakeBed
items.comment: A dried up or drained area of a former lake.
A sub-collection of PoliticalOrganization. Each instance is a group of people who try actively to influence legislation.
label: pressure group
Lobby-PoliticalOrganization

items.comment: A specialization of LinearObject_OneDimensional and LinearObject_Finite (qq.v.). Each instance of LineSegment is a finite, continuous portion of a Line (q.v.). It might be straight or curved. It might be bounded (i.e. have two endpoints), semi-bounded (one endpoint; e.g. noose-shaped), or unbounded (no endpoints; e.g. ring-shaped). Specializations of LineSegment include LineSegment_Straight and LineString.
label: portion of a line
LineSegment
integrating a set of knowledge sources
IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources
items.comment: IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources is the collection of all CWCreation events in which two or more StructuredKnowledgeSources are integrated to produce a new StructuredKnowledgeSource that is capable of storing all of the data stored in the input sources.
The collection of all instances of Article_PCW which are published in an instance of JournalIssue.
label: journal article
JournalArticle
light frigate
LightFrigate
items.comment: The collection of light frigate ships.

subClassOf: type of loan agreement classified by feature
label: type of loan agreement classified by interest rate option
LoanAgreementTypeByInterestRateOption
items.Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: types of loan agreement classified by interest rate option
items.comment: A collection of collections. Each instance of LoanAgreementTypeByInterestRateOption is a collection of LoanAgreements with the same interest rate option. Examples inculde IndexedLoan and FixedRateLoan.

label: Legionella pneumophila
LegionellaPneumophila
items.comment: The bacterium that causes Legionnaire's Disease (LegionnairesDisease) also known as legionellosis.

label: landing craft
LandingCraft
items.comment: The collection of watercraft or amphibious craft used in landing operations.
The collection of all lateral plantar nerves. The lateral plantar nerve is a branch of the TibialNerve and supplies the last 1 1/2 toes and the lateral muscles of the foot.
label: lateral plantar nerve
LateralPlantarNerve

items.comment: Heavy pads used to protect the knees from falls and other impacts.
label: knee pad
KneePad
interest
Interest
items.comment: A specialization of Situation (q.v.). Instances of Interest are temporal situations that an agent may (potentially) have an interest in maintaining or preserving or improving. Specializations include EconomicInterest.

label: ache
LevelOfDullThrobbingPain
items.comment: The type of internal sensation or feeling of a dull, throbbing pain.
The bone which protects the knee; aka patella.
label: kneecap
Kneecap

items.comment: The collection of all lipids - greasy, non-water-soluble organic compounds found in all living cells.
label: lipid
Lipid
semantic analysis
LinguisticAnalysis-Semantic
items.comment: A collection of microtheories.  Each element is a microtheory representing knowledge, theory, hypotheses, evidence, and problems related to the semantic analysis of a data set taken from a language or group of languages.

label: instant food
InstantFoodOrDrink
items.comment: A collection of stuff normally eaten or drunk by humans. Instances of InstantFood are instances of (FoodOrDrinkForFn Person) that are made from an instance of InstantFoodMix by adding other ingredients, mixing ingredients together, and/or heating or chilling. An instance of InstantFoodMix can be converted into an instance of InstantFood in a short amount of time, with a small amount of effort, equipment and expertise, and with the addition of only staple food items such as water, milk, eggs, etc. Examples include reconstituted frozen concentrated fruit juice, ramen noodles, and jello. Not included are foods that require only unwrapping or washing before eating. Something must be added, mixed together, and/or heated or chilled.

label: lateral segment of middle lobe of lung
LateralSegmentOfMiddleLobeOfLung
items.Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: lateral segments of middle lobe of lung
items.comment: The collection of all lateral segments of MiddleLobeOfLungs on the right side. Each is served by a LateralSegmentalBronchusOfMiddleLobeOfLung. (There is no lateral segment in the left Lung, since there is no middle lobe in the left lung.)

label: kneecap joint
KneeCapJoint
items.comment: The Kneecap articulates with both Condyles of the Femur (thigh bone).

label: lab glassware
LaboratoryGlassware
items.comment: A specialization of LaboratoryEquipment. Each instance of LaboratoryGlassware is glassware desgned to be used in a laboratory setting, for experiments. Important specializations include TestTube and Flask_LabGlassware.

label: JCAH accreditation
JCAHAccreditation
items.comment: A credential issued by the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Hospitals to hospitals that have been accredited in accordance with JCAH's rules and regulations.

label: embedding
LodgingInPlace
items.comment: A specialization of LocatingInIntendedPosition. Each instance of LodgingInPlace is an event in which an Agent_Generic puts something in a position where it will be held relatively firmly in place.

label: sharp pain
LevelOfSharpPain
items.comment: The type of internal sensation or feeling of a sharp pain.

label: intelligence analysis task
IntelligenceAnalysisTask-Allotment
items.comment: A specialization of Allotment that represents general intelligence analysis taskings.

label: KMF ontology term
KMFOntologyTerm
items.comment: The collection of terms created for the KMF ontology mapping.  Many instances are special case collections that closely correspond to the KMF OWL classes and properties.  Those special case terms that prove generally useful will be renamed and be available for general use.

label: Kodak camera
KodakCamera
items.comment: The collection of all Kodak cameras. A type of StillCamera. KodakCamera is a ProductTypeByBrand and a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType.

label: list template
ListTemplate
items.comment: The collection of parsing template categories that map to numbers.
An InfectiousDiseaseType, usually only affecting those instances of HomoSapiens with weakened immune systems and especially pregnant women. A serious case has a mortality risk of about 20%.
label: listeriosis
Listeriosis

items.comment: the collection of all lozenges.  A Lozenge is a medicated candy which dissolves in the mouth.
label: lozenge
Lozenge

items.comment: The subclass of Eclipse_CelestialEvent in which the Sun is obscured from view on MoonOfEarth by PlanetEarth. Realistically, this means that the PlanetEarth casts a visible Shadow across the surface of the MoonOfEarth. See also SolarEclipse.
label: lunar eclipse
LunarEclipse

items.comment: A LogOfWood is a log or section of a tree which is no longer living. Logs of wood may be sawn into short pieces and hence be considered Firewood, but not so processed as to be considered Lumber.
label: log
LogOfWood

items.comment: The collection of all laptop computers. A type of BatteryPoweredDevice, PortableObject, and PersonalComputer. The collection LaptopComputer is a ComputerHardwareDeviceType and a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType.
label: laptop computer
LaptopComputer
low-lying wetland
LowLyingWetland
items.comment: A specialization of WetlandRegion. Each LowLyingWetland is a wetland distinguished from Marshes by occuring in in low-lying wet areas, like the southern coast of Louisiana or Bangladesh. The U.S. military The USArmyFieldManual5_33VegetationMapCode assigns LowLyingWetland a Vegetation Map Code of (K).

JavaClass is a specialization of ProgramSpecification. Instances of JavaClass determine what sorts of operations programs written in JavaProgrammingLanguage are able to perform when they include the class and are interpreted by an instance of JavaVirtualMachine.
label: Java class
JavaClass

items.comment: A collection of events; a subcollection of BirthEvent. In each Laboring_BirthEvent, someone undergoes the efforts of childbirth.
label: laboring
Laboring-BirthEvent

items.comment: A collection of events; a subcollection of BringingAboutSomething. In each Leading_BringingAboutSomething, something results in something else.
label: leading
Leading-BringingAboutSomething
licensed-professional
Licensed-Professional
items.comment: The collection of instances of PersonWithOccupation that are licensed professionals, e.g., doctors and lawyers.

The collection of "kick," or "push" scooters, which are propelled by the user kicking or pushing off the ground with one foot, while standing on a wheeled platform with another.  Kick scooters roughly resemble thin skateboards with a long thin pole with handles in front.
label: push scooter
KickScooter
KAG
KnowledgeAcquisitionGoal
items.comment: The goal-category of acquiring knowledge.

label: interrogative utterance
InterrogativeUtterance
items.comment: The collection of interrogative  utterances issued in any language.

label: livestock route
LivestockRoute
items.comment: A specialization TravelRoute. Each instance of LivestockRoute is an established line of travel used to transport Livestock by herding them along.
The collection of all LCD displays. A type of ComputerDisplay. LiquidCrystalDisplay is a ComputerHardwareDeviceType and a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType.
label: LCD
LiquidCrystalDisplay

items.label: Kalua
items.comment: The collection of all Kalua. A type of CoffeeLiqueur.

label: lacrimal punctum
LacrimalPunctum
items.comment: The collection of all lateral puncta. An individual LacrimalPunctum is a portal of a LacrimalCanal in an Eyelid.

label: litter
Litter-Garbage
items.comment: Loose (unbagged) DomesticGarbage.  Litter is composed primarily of inorganic material.
The collection of all ink. A type of LiquidTangibleArtifact, LiquidTangibleThing, and ArtificialMaterial. Ink is TangibleStuffCompositionType.
label: ink
Ink
international unit of measure common
InternationalUnitOfMeasure-Common
items.comment: A specialization of InternationalUnitOfMeasure. Each instance of InternationalUnitOfMeasure_Common is an InternationalUnitOfMeasure that is used commonly in everyday life and is familiar to the average person (of a country in which the international, or metric, system is used). This is, of course, a vague criterion. A good rule of thumb: If a unit would likely be used in a newspaper article without explanation or definition, it belongs in this collection. Examples are Meter, MinutesDuration, Liter, Kilogram. Some non-examples are Parsec, Angstrom, Mole_ChemicalCountUnit.

label: lilac thing
LilacColor
items.comment: The collection of all lilac-colored things. A type of ColoredThing. LilacColor is a ChromaticColor.

label: intangible object describing predicate
IntangibleObjectPredicate
items.comment: A specialization of ObjectPredicate. This is the collection of predicates used to ascribe characteristics or properties (taken in a very broad sense) to intangible objects. As such, each instance of IntangibleObjectPredicate has at least one argument place (quite often including the first) constrained to accept only instances of IntangibleIndividual or some subcollection thereof. Examples include arg3Isa and religionOfRule.

label: fluorescent lamp
Lamp-Fluorescent
items.comment: The collection of all fluorescent lamps. A type of ElectricalLightingDevice and ManufacturedGoods. The collection Lamp_Fluorescent is a #$ManufacturedGoodsType, a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType, and an ArtifactTypeByGenericCategory.
The collection of all ivy. A type of Vine_Plant.
label: ivy
Ivy
electronic signal
LogicSignal
items.comment: Signals that take part in electronic circuits.

label: interval that is bounded at the top
Interval-BoundedAbove
items.Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: intervals that is bounded at the top
items.comment: A specialization of ScalarInterval. Each instance of Interval_BoundedAbove is an interval that has an upper bound. Example: the interval comprised by integers less than 10.

label: linea alba
LineaAlba
items.comment: The Collection of all LineaAlba (Abdominis) Tissues. The LineaAlba is located along the medial line of the Abdomen, connecting the PubicSymphysis to the XiphoidProcess and the RectusAbdominis Muscles to each other. Note that there is also a linea alba cervicalis in the Neck_AnimalBodyPart.

label: inventory buyer
InventoryBuyingAgent
items.comment: An employee who purchases inventory of a company. **

label: intervertebral disk
InterVertebralDisc
items.comment: The collection of all intervertebral disks. A type of InternalAnatomicalPart and AnimalBodyPart. The collection InterVertebralDisc is an InternalAnimalBodyRegionType, a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType, and an AnimalBodyPartType.

label: leader type by activity type influenced
LeaderTypeByActivityTypeInfluenced
items.comment: A collection of specializations of Leader. Each instance of LeaderTypeByActivityTypeInfluenced is such that all of the individuals in its extent share a common sphere of influence, understood as a type of activity (a subcollection of PurposefulAction), instances of which are shaped, in part, by the leadership efforts of those individuals. To tie an instance of LeaderTypeByActivityTypeInfluenced to the relevant activity-type, use leaderTypeHasInfluenceOverActivityType_Definitional.

A specialization of both Organization and LegalAgent. Each instance of LawEnforcementOrganization is an official organization whose purpose is to support or perform law enforcement. Instances of LawEnforcementOrganization include organizations which are legally empowered to enforce laws (see the specialization PoliceOrganization), as well as information agencies (such as INTERPOL) whose purpose is to assist and coordinate police activities.
items.Mx4rvjldVJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: law enforcement organization type by jurisdiction
label: law-enforcement organization
LawEnforcementOrganization
left subclavian to descending aorta graft
LeftSubclavianToDescendingAortaGraft-SurgicalProcedure
items.Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: left subclavian to descending aorta grafts

label: iranian education minister
IranianEducationMinister
items.comment: A specialization of Minister_Governmental and IranianPerson. An IranianEducationMinister heads the Iranian ministry that oversees education, and is the member of the IranianCabinet who advises the president on matters involving education.

label: interfering with an opponent
InterferingWithOpponent
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: will have interfered with an opponent
items.comment: The interfering with your opponents performance in ways not allowed by the rules of the game.

label: lisp reader
LispReader
items.comment: A specialization of DevelopmentProgram. Each instance of LispReader is a program designed to read Lisp code to generate a token stream to pass to a compiler or interpreter (see ProgrammingLanguageImplementation).
A kettle with a spout, handle, and lid, for boiling water on the stove top.
label: kettle
Kettle
logic high
LogicHigh
items.comment: Logic High signal.

label: kidnapping somebody sub events immersion of in person acid solution liquid
KidnappingSomebodySubEventsImmersionOfInPersonAcidSolution-Liquid

items.comment: A species of large toothed whale, also known as Orcas
label: killer whale
KillerWhale
Internet software
InternetSoftwareMarketCategory
items.comment: InternetSoftwareMarketCategory is the collection of software which is known and marketed as the particular 'internet software' market category within the software industry. It consists of programs that implement, extend or exploit (in significant ways) use of the Internet. Such programs, as available products, will usually be grouped together, in stores, in catalogues, etc. This market category includes some electronic mail products, programs of Internet service providers, and WorldWideWeb_DynamicIndexedInfoSource software, such as WorldWideWebServerPrograms and WorldWideWebClientPrograms.

label: law enforcement organization type by jurisdiction
LawEnforcementOrgTypeByJurisdiction
items.Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: law enforcement organization types by jurisdiction
items.comment: This type-level collection is intended to taxonomize the collection PoliceOrganization according to an important typology, namely the jurisdiction within which the organization is authorized to operate. Each instance of LawEnforcementOrgTypeByJurisdiction is a collection of PoliceOrganizations characterized by the fact that all instances operate within the same jurisdiction within some federal hierarchy: city, county, borough, state, national, etc.
The collection of all lingual arteries. A type of SystemicArtery. The concept LingualArtery is a SymmetricAnatomicalPartType and an InternalAnimalBodyRegionType.
label: lingual artery
LingualArtery
lifting
LiftingAnObject
items.comment: A collection of events; a subcollection of CausingAnotherObjectsTranslationalMotion. In each LiftingAnObject, something takes hold of something and moves it to a different location.

label: javelin throw field
JavelinThrowField
items.comment: The collection of fields where JavelinThrowSportsEvents usually occur.

label: KB dependent relation
KBDependentRelation
items.comment:
A collection of relations. Members of this collection are those predicates that are used (in the zeroth place of formulas) to express propositions whose truth depend on facts about the KB or functions whose mappings depend on the state of the CycKB (KB). A good example of a KBDependentRelation is assertedSentence. Whether or not it is true that (assertedSentence FORM) depends entirely upon whether or not FORM is asserted in the KB.

See also KBDependentCollection.
A sub-collection of Prayer_SacredText. Each instance is the prayer that Christ gave his disciples in the Sermon on the Mount (Matthew 6:9-13).
label: Lord's prayer
LordsPrayer
lavoltidine
Lavoltidine
items.comment: The collection of all lavoltidine. A type of DrugSubstance. Lavoltidine is a ChemicalCompoundTypeByChemicalSpecies.

label: likes and dislikes predicate
LikesPredicate
items.comment: The collection of predicates that relate agents to things they like (or things they dislike).

label: ground
LandStuff
items.comment: A specialization of NaturalTangibleStuff. Each instance of LandStuff is a portion of the stuff that the ground of a planet (at or near its land surface) is made of, including rocks, boulders, sand grains, soil, mud, lava, and mixtures of those things (such as islands or whole continents). Examples of LandStuff include ContinentOfAustralia, CapeCod, Zion Hill, and the lava pouring out of MountEtna_Volcano.

label: investment department
InvestmentDepartment
items.comment: Each instance of InvestmentDepartment consists of employees who are responsible for an organization's investments.

label: internally querying KB
InternallyQueryingKB
items.comment: The collection of all events of a #$SoftwareAgent asking for some information from some KnowledgeBase.
A piece (i.e., specific collections of nearby molecules) of lead; typically, these will be tightly bound into solid form.
label: lead
Lead

items.comment: An instance of TemporalStuffType and a specialization of LegalProceeding and GroupActivity. Each instance of Legislating is a PoliticalEvent in which Legislators debate, pass Laws, and engage in other official political activity.
label: legislating
Legislating
issuing a writ
IssuingAWrit
items.comment: An AccomplishmentType and specialization of Informing. Each instance of IssuingAWrit is a LegalProceeding in which a Court_Judicial issues a Writ.

label: instance level script microtheory
InstanceLevelScriptMicrotheory
items.comment: Microtheories of this type should detail an event by giving a list of subevents and temporal orderings of these subevents. Such microtheories should also contain a claim of what type of event the collection of subevents is supposed to be an instance of. See cyclistNotes on SubeventSequenceGraphMt for a method of conformity checking scripts with their script type in terms of temporal ordering.

label: interior surface tangible
InteriorSurface-Tangible
items.comment: A specialization of SurfaceRegion_Tangible. This is the collection of all surfaces of the interiors of tangible things. The tangible thing may have a Cavity or several cavities or passageways. Often the tangible thing can be thought of as a container of some sort.

label: losing a leaf
LosingALeaf
items.comment: The event in which some Plant loses a Leaf, due to lack of water, ailment, or in preparation for winter. This does not include events in which a leaf is pulled off by some other physical object.

label: levator scapulae muscle
LevatorScapula
items.comment: The Collection of all instances of LevatorScapula Muscle. The LevatorScapula, located in the Back_AnimalBodyPart, connects the Scapula to the CervicalVertebrae so as to raise the Scapula.

label: the Kyasanur virus
KyasanurForestDisease-Virus
items.comment: A specialization of Virus. KyasanurForestDisease_Virus is the type of virus that causes instances of KyasanurForestDisease.

label: large building
LargeBuilding
items.comment: The collection LargeBuilding is the collection of all buildings that are generally considered to be large compared to other buildings.
The collection of all keels, which are large beams around which the hulls of ships are built. A type of BoatOrShipPart. Keel is a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType.
label: keel
Keel

items.comment: A sub-collection of CalendarSystem. Each instance is a calendar based on lunar cycles.
label: lunar calendar
LunarCalendar
landscape image
LandscapeImage
items.comment: The collection of visual images which depict mainly geographical or topographical regions.  The depicted region itself is the focal object of the image.

label: joint venture
JointVentureActivity
items.comment: A collection of events. Each instance of JointVentureActivity is a business activity in which two or more independent companies cooperate to work on a business project mutually beneficial to all. During the venture, each participant is a partner to the others (see businessPartners). Joint ventures are always governed by at least one explicit Agreement.
A sub-collection of PromotingSomeone. Each instance is the ceremonial act of clothing someone in the insignia of an office; the formal promotion of a person to an office or rank.
label: investment
Investment-PromotingSomeoneInACeremony
hand-powered lawn mower
LawnMower-HandPowered
items.comment: The collection of old-fashioned hand-pushed and hand-powered lawnmowers, whose blades are powered by the user pushing the mower. A subset of LawnMower_HandPushed.

items.subClassOf: interfacing between computer device and OS
label: interfacing between mouse and OS
InterfacingBetweenMouseAndOS
items.comment: A collection of actions performed by computers. In each instance of InterfacingBetweenMouseAndOS, a MouseDriver interfaces between a ComputerMouse and the operating system; permitting the latter to manipulate the former in a standard way.

label: internal intercostal series
InternalIntercostalSeries
items.comment: The Collection of all sets of InternalIntercostal Muscles. Instances are series of InternalIntercostal Muscles on one side of the body of an Organism_Whole.

label: the jet stream
JetStream
items.comment: A specialization of PrevailingWind (q.v.). Each instance of JetStream is a fast and narrow air current that occurs high above the surface of the Earth, just under the Tropopause_PlanetEarth.

The collection of all law firms, which are companies that sell the legal services of lawyers. A type of ProfessionalServiceOrganization, OrganizationOfPeopleOnly, PrivateSectorOrganization, and CommercialServiceOrganization.
label: law firm
LawFirm
jewelry cleaner
JewelryCleaner
items.comment: The collection of all jewelry cleaners. A type of CleaningSubstance. The concept JewelryCleaner is an ArtifactTypeByGenericCategory and a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType.

label: Inuit
InuitLanguageFamily
items.comment: A sub-family of the EskimoLanguageFamily, consisting of languages primarily spoken in Alaska, Canada, and Greenland.

label: innominate artery to pulmonary artery conduit
InnominateArteryToPulmonaryArteryConduit-SurgicalProcedure
items.Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: innominate artery to pulmonary artery conduits

label: electric knife
Knife-Electric
items.comment: The collection of all electric knives. A type of CarvingKnife and ElectricalHouseholdAppliance. The collection Knife_Electric is a DeviceTypeByFunction, a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType, and a #$ManufacturedGoodsType.

label: inventory controller
InventoryControlPerson
items.comment: Someone who keeps track of a company's inventory.  This probably includes some security functions.

label: justification truth
JustificationTruth
items.comment: Instances of JustificationTruth are attribute values which indicate the provability status of a justification for an assertion in a context. The two most important examples are True_JustificationTruth and False_JustificationTruth. See also assertionTruth.

label: insecure script source code fault
InsecureScriptSourceCodeFault
items.comment: A program has an InsecureScriptSourceCodeFault if a specially-formed input to that program will yield the source code of a script used by that program to an unauthorized user. This is a common problem for web server programs.

label: luggage tag
LuggageTag
items.comment: The collection of all luggage tags. A type of Tag_IBO and TravelAccessory. The collection LuggageTag is an #$AerodromeCollection, a SpatiallyDisjointObjectType, and an ArtifactTypeByGenericCategory.

label: inland sea
InlandSea
items.comment: A specialization of Lake. Each instance of InlandSea is a large body of salt water (of second rank in relation to an Ocean) that is entirely, or almost entirely, land-locked.

label: left bundle branch posterior fascicle
LeftBundleBranchPosteriorFascicle
items.comment: The LeftBundleBranch includes two fascicles of Purkinje fibers that enervates a large number of myocytes in the Myocardium: the LeftBundleBranchAnteriorFascicle and the LeftBundleBranchPosteriorFascicle.

label: word formation process
LexicalWordFormationProcess
items.comment: A collection of collections. Elements of LexicalWordFormationProcess group word formings according to formation method. Example: DerivationalPrefixation is a kind of LexicalWordFormationProcess involving the agglutination of a LexicalPrefix to either a RootWord or a DerivedWord.

label: left ventricular heart failure
LeftVentricularHeartFailure
items.comment: A kind of HeartFailure characterized by the inability of the left ventricle (see LeftVentricle) to pump blood into the body. Left ventricular heart failure can be the result of a stiff ventricle that fails to allow the chamber to fill with blood, in which case it is diastolic (see DiastolicHeartFailure); or it can be the result of a weak ventricle than cannot pump blood out of the chamber, in which case the failure is systolic (see SystolicHeartFailure).

label: intelligence agent
IntelligenceAgent
items.comment: The collection consisting of every Professional_Adult who is an employees of some GovernmentIntelligenceOrganization.

label: lower eyelid
LowerEyelid

A specialization of Event_Localized. Each instance of IntrinsicStateChangeEvent is an event characterized primarily by a change in some intrinsic property of at least one main actor involved in the event. Such intrinsic changes may include changes of a thing's color, temperature, device state, or size. Events where the main change is extrinsic (such as a change in location or ownership) are not instances of IntrinsicStateChangeEvent. In events which have more than one actor, the event may be an IntrinsicStateChangeEvent for one actor but not for another. For example, in a FasteningSafetyBelt event, the SafetySeatBelt (the device used) goes from unconnected to connected (to itself), which is an intrinsic change; however, the agent who does the fastening does not change intrinsically, but only in his configuration to the belt, an external object. Another example: in a HairCuttingEvent, the hair that is cut undergoes an IntrinsicStateChangeEvent due to its role in that kind of event, but the barber undergoes no intrinsic change due to the hair cutting.

Note that some events, such as an ice cube melting into a small puddle of water, could be represented either as an IntrinsicStateChangeEvent or as a PhysicalTransformationEvent, but not (within a single micro-theory) as both.

label: KB dependent collection
KBDependentCollection
items.comment:
A specialization of TimeDependentCollection (q.v.). This is the collection of all and only those collections COL such that any thing's being an instance of COL depends on the current state of the CycKB. Such a COL corresponds to a property defined (at least partly) in terms of the contents, features, or implementation of the Cyc Knowledge Base itself, as opposed to a property that "exists out there" in the KB-independent world.

For example, CycLAssertion is a KB-dependent collection, membership in which requires of a given CycL sentence that it has in fact been asserted to the KB. CycLSentence is also KB-dependent, as being a CycL sentence requires being composed (ultimately) out of CycLReifiedDenotationalTerms (and perhaps variables) -- i.e. terms that are currently reified in the KB. Conversely, Sentence is not a KB-dependent collection.

See also KBDependentRelation.

items.comment: A specialization of Execution_Judicial. Each instance of LethalInjection_Execution is an execution of an agent in punishment for some crime in which drugs are administered to the agent to induce death. First the agent is hooked up to IntravenousEquipment and started on a saline solution. The agent is anesthesized, typically with the barbituate sodium thiopental. A saline solution will flush the IV again, and the the agent usually receives a paralyzing agent like pancuronium bromide to stop the breathing. After another IV flush, some states also include a final toxic agent to induce cardiac arrest with something like potassium chloride.

Muslims [see MuslimPerson] believe that on this date in (YearFn 610), MuhammadTheProphet first received the revelations of the Koran.

items.comment: An instance of TangibleStuffStateType and a specialization of FluidTangibleThing; the collection of all portions of liquid. Each instance of LiquidTangibleThing is a tangible thing that has similar properties to those exhibited by things in the Liquid_StateOfMatter. Specifically, its volume is relatively constant at varying pressures, and it freely changes shape (e.g. to conform to the shape of its container). Liquids can never be said to break. Note that not all LiquidTangibleThings are in Liquid_StateOfMatter : state-of-matter attributes (see MatterTypeByPhysicalState) apply only to quantities consisting of a single type of substance, whereas liquids can be mixtures of different substances. Examples of LiquidTangibleThings include all substances in the Liquid_StateOfMatter, such as the water in a room-temperature glass of beer; liquid/liquid mixtures like the beer itself; solutions of solids in liquids, such as sea water; emulsions, such as milk; and suspensions of solids in liquids, like blood. Compare FluidTangibleThing and GaseousTangibleThing.

label: looking for something indefinite

items.comment: This is the collection of lookings where the seeker has a particular PossibleIdentificationCondition but does not believe that exactly one thing satisfies it. It is not required that the seeker believe that more than one thing satisfies it, although this will often be the case. The agent might have consciously in mind one or more descriptions of the sort of thing s/he is seeking or, if not, could at least be prompted to produce such descriptions. Some of these descriptions will express properties the seeker would take to be criterial of success in the sense that s/he could not conceive of a case in which both (i) s/he successfully finds an object of that type and (ii) the object s/he finds lacks any of those properties. The conjunction of these criterial properties will correspond to the instance of PossibleIdentificationCondition that is associated with the search (see searchCriterion_Indefinite). There are two rather different varieties of this sort of looking. In the first sort, the seeker is after just one thing and any thing that satisfies the identification condition will minimally suffice. In the second sort, the seeker is looking for multiple instances of some type of thing. See LookingForSomething_IndefiniteSingle and LookingForSomething_IndefiniteMultiple.

label: luminescence dating
LuminescenceDating
items.comment:
While some charge traps in minerals are sensitive to heat, others are extremely sensitive to light. When an irradiated quartz or feldspar sample is
exposed to visible or even infrared photons, the trapped electrons are evicted from these light-sensitive deep traps. They promptly undergo
recombination, and in doing so emit photons in the visible spectrum. Careful wavelength restriction of the stimulating light, combined with strict
filtering of the photons emitted by the sample, allows detection of the recombination luminescence. The amount of light emitted is proportional to
the mineral's intrinsic sensitivity to radiation and the total amount of radiation energy absorbed. Comparisons made of the light emitted by a natural
sample and the amount of light emitted by a sample with a known added radiation dose, plus separate dosimetry measurements, allow the sample's
age since it was last exposed to a "clock-resetting event" to be calculated. For optical dating, also sometimes referred to as OSL (optically stimulated luminescence) dating, the clock-resetting event is the exposure to
sunlight which sediment grains undergo during transport and the process of sedimentation. Optical dating is therefore suitable for the dating of a
wide variety of unheated sedimentary deposits laid down within the last ~500,000 years.

label: Kerberos KDC spoofing fault
KerberosKDCSpoofingFault
items.comment:
Kerberos is a cryptographic authentication protocol that allows users
 of a network to access services without transmitting cleartext
 passwords. A common implementation of the protocol includes a login
 service which is vulnerable to an attack which involves spoofing
 responses from the Key Distribution Center (KDC). The login service
 authenticates a user by first requesting a ticket granting ticket
 (TGT) from the authentication server. If the TGT can be decrypted
 using the password supplied by the user, the login service attempts to
 verify the identity of the KDC by making a request with the received
 TGT for a service ticket for itself. The service ticket returned by
 the KDC is encrypted with a secret shared between the KDC and the
 service host. If the service ticket cannot be verified with the
 service's secret key it is assumed that the KDC is not authentic. If
 the login service has not been registered as a principal with the KDC
 or the service's secret key has not been installed on the host the
 login service will proceed without verification that the TGT was
 returned by the authentic KDC. In these circumstances it is possible   
 to log into the server illicitly if an attacker can spoof responses
 from the Key Distribution Center. If these circumstances occur then a
 program has this fault.

label: left and right sided object
LeftAndRightSidedObject
items.comment: A LeftAndRightSidedObject is an object with an intrinsic left side and an intrinsic right side. By 'intrinsic' we mean simply that there exists an established convention according to which one side is considered 'Left' and the other side is considered 'Right'. Usually, the two sides can be reliably distinguished from one another. Notice that a conventionally distinguishable left and right do not necessarily imply a bottom and top, or a front and back. Interestingly, it has proved impossible so far to find instances of objects with a left and right but no top, bottom, front or back. It is unclear why this should be so, but it apparently pertains to human psychology in reasoning about directions. However, if an object has a conventionally distinguished top, bottom, front, and back, then these suffice to determine an intrinsic left and an intrinsic right. Notice also--and this is crucial to the whole conception--that while a LeftAndRightSidedObject may well have a preferred orientation, changing this orientation does not change what counts as 'left' and what counts as 'right': if you turn me upside down my left side does not become my right side and my right side my left. If an entity does not obey this rule then it does not, generally speaking, count as having a distinguishable left and right--example: a houseplant.

label: international alliance
InternationalAlliance
items.comment: The collection of all agreements between geopolitical agents where the parties to the agreement agree to work in concert with respect to some endeavor or set of issues. An international alliance may be formed for a comparatively specific purpose, like the DesertShieldCoalition, or it may be formed with a wide range of goals in mind, like the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Also, alliances may be relatively brief or may be quite long-standing. Alliances are often established through some sort of formal treaty. Their participants are almost always instances of IndependentCountry acting as international agents. A situation where one or more of the participants is an international corporation like the Lippo Group or Saudi Aramco, or some other global economic entity like the International Monetary Fund, might conceivably be a borderline case.

label: inter arg equals isa predicate
InterArgEqualsIsaPredicate
items.comment:
The subcollection of both InterArgTypePredicate and ArgIsaPredicate (qq.v.) whose instances are used to put conditional isa based argument-type constraints on polyadic relations in regards to one of their argument-places, when another argument-place is filled by a particular value. Each instance of InterArgEqualsIsaPredicate specifies, with respect to a given Relation, that one of its arguments (the "dependent" one) must be an instance of (isa) a certain collection, contingent upon another of its argument's (the "independent" one's) being a particular specified thing.

An inter-argument-exact-isa predicate PRED has at least three argument-places, for designating, respectively: the relation RELN being constrained, the collection serving as the (conditional) argument-type constraint for RELN's dependent argument, and the thing that must serve as RELN's independent argument for the constraint to be in effect. The (numerically-specified) positions of RELN's independent and dependent arguments is in most cases fixed (as in the ternary interArgEqualsIsa1_2), but in the case of the quintary interArgEqualsIsa it is variable and specified via two additional argument-places.

lexical slot
LexicalSlot
items.comment: The collection LexicalSlot exists mainly to propagate values for threshold, aPrioriLikelihood, and defaultCF. It is not clear to me that these slots are meaningful in this context, but the system forces me to include them. If have tried to choose values reflecting the precise nature of the lexical enterprise. That is, although any particular usage of the word `flower' may be ambiguous, it is nearly certain that in general, the objects which are in fact flowers are among the possible meanings of flower. As for the threshold, we don't want lexical entries unless the lexicographer is quite certain he is right. As for aPrioriLikelihood, it is highly unlikely that, for example, some arbitrarily choosen word will have among its possible meanings some arbitrarily choosen concept. The number .01 was choosen based on the estimated size of CYC's lexica for the forseeable future. Another possible value of this unit is simply as an organizing concept allowing lexicographers quick access to the existing slots relevant to their interests.

label: linear object non planar

A specialization of LinearObject (q.v.). LinearObject_NonPlanar is the collection of all linearly-shaped objects, whether tangible or intangible, that are not embeddable (even roughly) in a Plane, and thus are only embeddable in a three-dimensional space region. Since a LinearObject can itself be three-dimensional, we stipulate that non-planar 3-D a linear-object is not even embeddable in a FlatSurfaceRegion (q.v.).

Note that the criterion for being "non-planar" in the present sense varies from context to context. For example, the standard of non-planarity for the manufacture of wrought-iron railing is less precise than that for pure geometry.

Specializations of LinearObject_NonPlanar include Spiral. And cf. LinearObject_Planar.

items.comment: A InterimVehicleMountedMineDetector (IVMMD) is used for route clearance missions and to precede convoys. It is a vehicle-mounted mine detection and marking system for use on-road and is capable of being teleoperated. It only detects metallic mines. As a 'non-developmental item' system, it may have a lower probability of detection and higher false alarm rate than the objective GroundStamids system. IVMMD is mounted on blast-resistant vehicles which are field repairable following a mine detonation. It has low ground-pressure tires and the second detection vehicle tows proofing trailers to detonate mines which are missed by the metal detector sensors. (Source: Engineer Systems Handbook, 4/97)

items.comment: The subcollection of both InterArgConstraintPredicate and ArgFormatPredicate (qq.v.) whose instances are used to specify, for a given predicate PRED, a certain Format requirement on one of PRED's arguments (the "dependent" one), contingent upon one (usually, but not always, a different one) of PRED's arguments (the "independent" one) being an instance of (isa) a certain collection. Currently, each instance of InterArgFormatPredicate is ternary, where its first argument (or "arg1") is the predicate PRED upon which the constraint is being placed, its arg2 the collection serving as the isa condition on PRED's independent argument, and its arg3 the Format that PRED's dependent argument is (conditionally) constrained to have. IrregularMilitaryForce
items.comment:
A specialization of MilitaryOrganization. Each instance of IrregularMilitaryForce is a military organization that is not regularly established, but rather, exists in connection with (and usually only for the duration of) a specific conflict or situation. A group member of an irregular military force might be a regular (instance of) MilitaryPerson who is assigned a special military task very different from his usual ones, or might be someone who is not regularly a MilitaryPerson at all but is nevertheless assigned a military task.

For example, suppose a Central American army officer organized a group of villagers to help defend against an impending invasion. The group would for a time constitute a part of the country's irregular army force -- which force would itself be an instance of (IrregularForcesFn Army_BranchOfService).

items.comment: A specialization of OfficialDocument. While OfficialDocuments such as CreditReportDocuments may have legal force in some contexts, they are not considered LegalDocuments because their construction is not as tightly specified by law as that of LegalDocuments. iterated event scene
IteratedEventScene
items.comment: IteratedEventScene is an instance of #$ScriptedEventType (q.v.). Specializations of IteratedEventScene are event-types which are scenes in scripts, and which are themselves types of scripted events in which some event is repeated in sequence at least twice, possibly indefinitely, and sometimes until a terminal condition (such as a goal event) is achieved. By convention, the terminal state type is considered to be a sub-event type of the iterated event type, but it need not be the same type as the iterated event. For example, mixing a cake batter may involve iterations of stirring the batter, and they are terminated when the batter reaches a certain consistency, but reaching a consistency is not itself a stirring. Some terminal conditions of iterated event types are of the same kind as the iterated events -- for example, in a script that requires taking eight leaps, taking the 8th leap may be the terminal event, and it itself is a leap (which is also the iterated event type).

Each Kaleidoscope is a toy which one looks into to see symmetrical patterns of moving colors. Kaleidoscopes are generally cylindrical, with an eye-hole at one end, and with a compartment at the far end which contains colored objects that can move freely within the compartment. The far end is either translucent or transparent, so that light can enter. The inside walls of a kaleidoscope have mirrors, usually two set at an angle, so that when the compartmentalized objects move around, they appear to be multiplied N-fold (depending on the angle of the mirrors) and moving in symmetry with their reflections.

label: joint-physical
Joint-Physical
items.comment: A specialization of Connection_Physical. Each instance of Joint_Physical is a group consisting of parts of at least two instances of PartiallyTangible that are mechanically connected in the manner of a joint. Examples include an elbow, and a hinge joining a door to a frame. While each Joint_Physical is an instance of PartiallyTangible, and therefore has a determinate spatial boundary, there are many cases in which there are no easily describable boundaries between the parts of joint-connected objects that are parts of the joint, and those which are not. For example, consider a ball and socket joint connecting some hip bone to a femur. The boundaries of this joint are obscure due to the fact that exact boundaries of the socket portion of the hip and the ball of the femur are obscure. In contrast, the spatial boundaries of a joint comprising a detachable hinge, such as those that typically connect a door to frame, are clear.

label: local chain organization

A local chain organization may be a corporation in its own right while still being a sub-organization of the larger organization whose franchising agreements control or constrain the business operations of the local organization. Note that a LocalChainOrganization need not be a SingleSiteOrganization.

items.comment: The collection of instances of LookingForAThingOrTypeOfThing wherein some IntelligentAgent is looking for a particular thing. The agent might have consciously in mind one or more descriptions of the thing s/he is seeking or, if not, could at least be prompted to produce such descriptions. Some of these descriptions will express properties the seeker would take to be criterial of success in the sense that s/he could not conceive of a case in which both (i) s/he successfully finds the object and (ii) the object s/he finds lacks any of those properties. The conjunction of these criterial properties will correspond to the instance of PossibleIdentificationCondition that is associated with the search (see searchCriterion_Definite). What makes an instance of LookingForAThingOrTypeOfThing an instance of LookingForSomething_Definite is that the agent believes that exactly one object has this conjunction of criterial properties, namely the particular object s/he seeks.

items.comment: A specialization of PhysicalQuantity, each instance of LevelOfSubstanceInSystem is a qualitative or quantitative "measure" of the level of some substance in a system where the substance is of a type _standardly_ found in the relevant system type. items.comment: A subcollection of SocialGatheringAtResidence. In each instance of InvitedDiningAtResidence, the focal sub-event is a meal provided for the guest or guests (guestAtSocialGathering, qv.) by the host. Typically, the guest and host share the meal, often with others (e.g., family members of the host). It is also typical for the meal to have been prepared by the host and/or some of her close associates (family, roomates, servants), though it is possible for the meal to be catered. In some instances of InvitedDiningAtResidence, guests contribute to the meal in minor ways, e.g., by bringing side dishes they purchased or prepared. But a true 'pot-luck' dinner would not be an instance of InvitedDiningAtResidence.
